ttributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47951"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4356"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first pregnancy visit at 12 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A dating ultrasound is performed which shows a twin pregnancy. The sonographer notes a thick membrane between the fetuses and a triangular projection of placental tissue extending between the layers of the dividing membrane where it meets the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of twin pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monochorionic diamniotic twins","Monochorionic monoamniotic twins","Dichorionic monoamniotic twins","Dichorionic diamniotic twins","Conjoined twins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound findings described in this case are classic for dichorionic diamniotic (DCDA) twins. The key finding is the \u0027lambda sign\u0027 or \u0027twin peak sign\u0027, which appears as a triangular projection of placental tissue extending between the layers of the dividing membrane where it meets the placenta. This sign, along with a thick dividing membrane, is pathognomonic for \u003Cstrong\u003Edichorionic diamniotic twins\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonochorionic diamniotic twins\u003C/strong\u003E show a different appearance on ultrasound, with a thin dividing membrane that meets the placenta at right angles, creating a \u0027T-sign\u0027. These twins share a placenta but have separate amniotic sacs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonochorionic monoamniotic twins\u003C/strong\u003E have no dividing membrane at all, as they share both a placenta and an amniotic sac. This is a rare and high-risk type of twin pregnancy, occurring in approximately 1% of monozygotic twins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjoined twins\u003C/strong\u003E are an extremely rare type of monochorionic monoamniotic twins where the embryo fails to completely separate. They would appear as inseparable fetuses on ultrasound with shared body parts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDichorionic monoamniotic twins\u003C/strong\u003E do not exist as a biological entity. If there are two chorions, there must be two amnions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDetermining chorionicity is crucial as it impacts pregnancy management and outcomes. DCDA twins have the best prognosis as each fetus has its own placenta and amniotic sac. The assessment of chorionicity is most accurate when performed in the first trimester or early second trimester (before 14 weeks gestation), as the lambda sign may disappear in later pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dichorionic diamniotic twins can be identified by the presence of a thick dividing membrane with a \u0027lambda\u0027 or \u0027twin peak\u0027 sign at the placental insertion.","Monochorionic diamniotic twins show a thin dividing membrane with a \u0027T-sign\u0027 at the placental insertion.","Early ultrasound (\u003C14 weeks) is most reliable for determining chorionicity in twin pregnancies."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Twin and triplet pregnancy [Internet]. London: NICE; 2019 [cited 2024 Nov 17]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng137/resources/twin-and-triplet-pregnancy-pdf-66141724389829"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47951"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47951"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T22:11:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T22:12:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,